  1. Lets open the data
MichFlickr <- read.csv("MichiganFlickr.csv")
  1. First lets look at distribution of the data. To plot time series data, we need to change the formate so R understand that it should be read a date. We do this by coersing it using ad.Date or as.POSIXct function. This is part of the package Lubridate, which is helpful for time series data. It can also be used to grab/parse specific parts of a date (e.g year, month etc.)
MichFlickr$date <- as.POSIXct(MichFlickr$dateupload, origin="1970-01-01")
MichFlickr$date <- as.Date(format(MichFlickr$date, format="%Y-%m-%d"))
###We will also give it a value. We want to count the number of photos 
MichFlickr$year <- year(MichFlickr$date)
MichFlickr$month <- month(MichFlickr$date, label = TRUE)
MichFlickr$day <- day(MichFlickr$date)
MichFlickr$count<- 1
MichFlickr$Nature<- MichFlickr$predict_Na > 0.6
  1. To plot time series, we need to summarise the photos per day. We will use the mutate, group_by and summarise function to create this new table
daily_photography <- MichFlickr %>%
  mutate(day = as.Date(date, format="%Y-%m-%d")) %>%
  group_by(day) %>% # group by the day column
  summarise(total_photos=sum(count)) %>%  # calculate the SUM of all precipitation that occurred on each day
  na.omit()

7.Lets check if there is a monthly pattern of sharing photograph through Flickr. First we will use the mutate() function to parse the month and year from the date data. Here we are using the lubridate function to grab this data. Here is a cheatsheet for the lubridate package. We will summerize the total number of photographs based on the year and month using group_by (sometimes there are issues with this function due to different package dependancies dplyer and ggplot).

daily_monthly <- daily_photography %>%
    mutate(month =  month(ymd(daily_photography$day), label = TRUE, abbr = FALSE),
           year  = year(as.Date(day, format = "%Y-%m-%d"))) %>%
    group_by(year,month) %>%
    summarise(total.qty = sum(total_photos))

  1. Now we will plot the peaks and valleys by adding the stat_peaks and stat_valleys argument to the typical ggplot format. The arguments indicate what color to give and the time series peaks and valleys. We also have to use the POSIXct.
daily_nature_only  %>%  
    filter(year == '2011' & month=='December')  %>% 
ggplot(aes(x = as.POSIXct(date), y = total_photos), as.numeric = FALSE) + 
  geom_line() + 
  stat_peaks(colour = "red") +
  stat_peaks(geom = "text", colour = "red", angle = 45,
               vjust = 1.5, hjust = 1,  x.label.fmt = "%d%B") +
  stat_valleys(colour = "blue") +
 stat_valleys(geom = "text", colour = "blue", angle = 360,

Lets assume that locations of Nature and Not-Nature Photos will be spatially and temporaly different, that we can calculate the mean point(mean lons & mean lats) of each dates photo taking locations, and use line to connect the points in a sequence and use different colors to display them by month. Here are the animation of the route of Nature type photos mean points:

library(transformr)
## Warning: package 'transformr' was built under R version 4.3.2
library(tidyr)
animateMichNature <-animateMich %>% 
filter(date >= as.Date('2010-01-01') & date <= as.Date('2010-12-31') & Nature == "TRUE") 

# Calculate mean points on each day and add month column
mean_point_Nature <- animateMichNature %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(mean_lon = mean(longitude, na.rm = TRUE),
            mean_lat = mean(latitude, na.rm = TRUE)) %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(date))

p3 <- mich + theme_void() + 
  geom_polygon(data = mich_county, fill = NA, color = "white") +
  geom_polygon(color = "black", fill = NA) +
  geom_point(data = animateMichNature, aes(longitude, latitude), inherit.aes = FALSE) +
  # Plot the historical mean points with geom_path before the transition
  geom_path(data = mean_point_Nature, aes(mean_lon, mean_lat, group = 1, color = as.factor(month)), size = 1.5) +
  geom_point(data = mean_point_Nature, aes(mean_lon, mean_lat, group = 1, color = as.factor(month)), size = 3) +
  transition_reveal(date) +
  # Optional: Add a legend title for the colour aesthetic
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Month")

animate(p3, fps = 2)
## `geom_path()`: Each group consists of only one observation.
##  Do you need to adjust the group aesthetic?

From the result we can see that the mean points seems distribute more tightly in lower bottom part in Lower Peninsula, majorly around large cities like Grand Rapids, Lansing and Detroit. Whats more, we can plot the variance of longitudes and latitudes of Nature and Not-Nature type photos to see the difference of their changing trends during a year.

variance_nature <- mean_point_Nature %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(date)) %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(var_lon = var(mean_lon, na.rm = TRUE),
            var_lat = var(mean_lat, na.rm = TRUE))

variance_notNature <- mean_point_notNature %>%
  mutate(month = lubridate::month(date)) %>%
  group_by(month) %>%
  summarise(var_lon = var(mean_lon, na.rm = TRUE),
            var_lat = var(mean_lat, na.rm = TRUE))

variance_nature$type <- "nature"
variance_notNature$type <- "notnature"
combined_df <- bind_rows(variance_nature, variance_notNature)

# Now, plot the combined data frame
# Plot variance of longitude
ggplot(combined_df, aes(x = month, y = var_lon, color = type)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Variance of Longitude", 
       title = "Variance of Longitude by Month",
       color = "Dataframe")

# Plot variance of latitude
ggplot(combined_df, aes(x = month, y = var_lat, color = type)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Month", y = "Variance of Latitude", 
       title = "Variance of Latitude by Month",
       color = "Dataframe")

From the graphs we can summarize these characteristics of the variance of lons and lats: (1) Nature and Not-Nature photos variance of Longitude&Latitude will show different changing trend from June to November, which happen seems to be the non-snowing seasons of Michigan, that indicates that people/tourists will separately doing nature activities(taking Nature photos) and non-nature activities(taking Not-Nature photos) in different places during these months. (2) Both Nature photos variance of Longitude&Latitude are greater than Non-Nature variance, that indicates that places that people willing to taking Nature photos are more disperse than places taking Non-Nature photos.
